WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.850 --> 00:00:03.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, D.C.

00:00:20.050 --> 00:00:20.300
&gt;&gt; Maria A. Palante: For those

00:00:20.300 --> 00:00:23.960
of you just joining us we had an
incredibly stimulating morning

00:00:23.960 --> 00:00:27.010
this morning and a
wonderful keynote,

00:00:27.010 --> 00:00:31.290
and this afternoon we're going
to begin to hear from creators

00:00:31.290 --> 00:00:33.600
and before I say
that I just want

00:00:33.600 --> 00:00:36.870
to also again thank the
Center for the Protection

00:00:36.870 --> 00:00:39.080
of Intellectual Property.

00:00:39.080 --> 00:00:44.390
And over here you'll see very
intelligent energetic looking

00:00:44.390 --> 00:00:47.200
students, and I think,

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:49.630
if you don't mind I think
they're our future and I'd

00:00:49.630 --> 00:00:52.510
like to recognize them for
helping us to put this on today.

00:00:52.510 --> 00:00:57.380
[ Applause ]

00:00:57.380 --> 00:01:01.060
I also want to make a
point to thank John Conyers

00:01:01.060 --> 00:01:04.590
who is the Ranking Member of
the House Judiciary Committee.

00:01:04.590 --> 00:01:09.040
When I testified before
the committee in favor

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:10.900
of comprehensive
review of copyright law,

00:01:10.900 --> 00:01:12.650
the Copyright Office
made the point that no

00:01:12.650 --> 00:01:16.800
such review would be complete
without looking at moral rights.

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:21.770
And John Conyers who, has been
a lifelong advocate of authors

00:01:21.770 --> 00:01:25.840
and artists, asked us formally
to commence such a study.

00:01:25.840 --> 00:01:29.430
So as we said this morning,
this symposia cosponsored

00:01:29.430 --> 00:01:32.480
with George Mason Law
School is the beginning

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:34.900
of that public dialogue.

00:01:34.900 --> 00:01:37.800
And with that I'd like to
turn it over to Kim Isbell

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:40.940
who is Senior Counsel in
our Department of Policy

00:01:40.940 --> 00:01:43.670
and International Affairs.

00:01:43.670 --> 00:01:44.760
&gt;&gt; Kim Isbell: Thanks Maria.

00:01:44.760 --> 00:01:51.580
You know, as Maria just
alluded to one of the key things

00:01:51.580 --> 00:01:53.970
about this panel that I think is
really interesting is it's the

00:01:53.970 --> 00:01:57.390
first opportunity to really hear
from the artists themselves.

00:01:57.390 --> 00:02:01.310
You know this morning, we heard
from a lot of lawyers talking

00:02:01.310 --> 00:02:04.750
about what moral rights
the United States does

00:02:04.750 --> 00:02:08.700
or doesn't recognize, how
you could assert more rights

00:02:08.700 --> 00:02:11.610
under various provisions
of U.S. law

00:02:11.610 --> 00:02:14.440
and then the very
interesting keynote

00:02:14.440 --> 00:02:18.040
by Professor Ginsberg
talking about what she views

00:02:18.040 --> 00:02:21.480
as a very important moral
right, the right of attribution

00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:23.950
and how we could go
about codifying it.

00:02:23.950 --> 00:02:27.310
But this panel is
really focused on:

00:02:27.310 --> 00:02:30.470
what do artists themselves
think?

00:02:30.470 --> 00:02:34.480
How do moral rights impact
their day to day work?

00:02:34.480 --> 00:02:38.660
How do they impact them both
professionally and personally?

00:02:38.660 --> 00:02:40.910
Which moral rights
do they care about?

00:02:40.910 --> 00:02:45.340
Which moral rights make their
lives easier or more difficult?

00:02:45.340 --> 00:02:48.320
And so for that reason,

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:52.370
I'm going to take a slightly
different approach to this panel

00:02:52.370 --> 00:02:54.530
than we have in the
prior panels.

00:02:54.530 --> 00:02:57.690
I'm not going to start off
asking our panelists a bunch

00:02:57.690 --> 00:02:58.430
of questions.

00:02:58.430 --> 00:03:01.640
Instead I want to give each
of them about five minutes

00:03:01.640 --> 00:03:05.710
to really talk to you
from their own perspective

00:03:05.710 --> 00:03:10.840
as to what moral rights and
what this symposium mean to them

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:14.360
and what they think
should be the key takeaways

00:03:14.360 --> 00:03:18.250
as the Copyright Office is
going into a larger study

00:03:18.250 --> 00:03:20.120
of the issue of moral rights.

00:03:20.120 --> 00:03:22.730
Before I do that though
I am just quickly going

00:03:22.730 --> 00:03:24.270
