00:05:28.410 --> 00:05:29.400
&gt;&gt; Melvin Gibbs: Good afternoon.

00:05:29.400 --> 00:05:31.230
Howdy [laughter].

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:36.290
I was about to use
Kimberly but is it more --

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:39.400
, should I be saying Ms.
IsBell in this context?

00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:39.940
&gt;&gt; Kimberely: Kimberly is fine.

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:40.080
[launghter]

00:05:40.080 --> 00:05:41.510
&gt;&gt; Melvin: All right so
I'm going to say Kimberly

00:05:41.510 --> 00:05:44.140
so you know I'm trying to
get with the protocol here.

00:05:44.140 --> 00:05:48.350
Anyway as Kimberly said
earlier there was a lot of talk

00:05:48.350 --> 00:05:51.410
about the law and
intricacies of the law.

00:05:51.410 --> 00:05:55.430
I'm a musician.

00:05:55.430 --> 00:05:58.640
We think about the law as part

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:05.360
of a more holistic way
we think about the world.

00:06:05.360 --> 00:06:09.160
For me personally, in addition
to thinking about the law

00:06:09.160 --> 00:06:10.340
when I have to think
about it I think

00:06:10.340 --> 00:06:13.120
about what my music
means philosophically

00:06:13.120 --> 00:06:14.390
and what it means economically.

00:06:14.390 --> 00:06:22.680
And once I start thinking
about music, you know you have

00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:24.870
to start thinking about
how you translate it,

00:06:24.870 --> 00:06:28.410
and then it becomes a question
of thinking about metaphors.

00:06:28.410 --> 00:06:32.720
And as musicians we're basically
stuck in two metaphors.

00:06:32.720 --> 00:06:34.690
We are stuck in a metaphor
where we are workers;

00:06:34.690 --> 00:06:37.710
we are making a musical work.

00:06:37.710 --> 00:06:43.750
Or we are employees
creating a product.

00:06:43.750 --> 00:06:48.420
For me, neither one of
those things actually works.

00:06:48.420 --> 00:06:50.810
I actually think of myself
as part of a community

00:06:50.810 --> 00:06:53.660
and creating for a community.

00:06:53.660 --> 00:07:00.070
And in the context of this
society, the goal seems

00:07:00.070 --> 00:07:04.410
to be dissemination of
creativity, getting it out to

00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:07.130
as many people as possible.

00:07:07.130 --> 00:07:10.620
And the question becomes,
for somebody like me

00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:15.430
who is creative, is how am I
going to make that process work.

00:07:15.430 --> 00:07:16.480
Leaving aside the kind

00:07:16.480 --> 00:07:20.400
of inherent you know
heteronormative male aspect

00:07:20.400 --> 00:07:24.540
of the word dissemination you
have the question of [laughter],

00:07:27.580 --> 00:07:30.370
you have the question
of what does that mean?

00:07:30.370 --> 00:07:33.200
Dissemination is a process
that starts from an individual

00:07:33.200 --> 00:07:35.120
to another individual.

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:38.860
So inherently for the
dissemination process to work,

00:07:38.860 --> 00:07:42.180
the individual has
to be recognized.

00:07:42.180 --> 00:07:47.960
So how that works in the context
of a community is very simple.

00:07:47.960 --> 00:07:50.150
You know who the guy down
the street is who does X,

00:07:50.150 --> 00:07:53.500
Y or Z. For us as musicians,
there might be a guy--

00:07:53.500 --> 00:07:56.020
for me there was literally
the man who lived next door

00:07:56.020 --> 00:08:01.570
who started me off on music.

00:08:01.570 --> 00:08:05.450
The question becomes I needed
to know who this person was.

00:08:05.450 --> 00:08:09.900
In the context of a community,
of course you're going

00:08:09.900 --> 00:08:13.610
to know that, but in
the context of 2016

00:08:13.610 --> 00:08:19.370
when we have aggregated groups
of data it becomes difficult

00:08:19.370 --> 00:08:25.400
to impossible to know who these
individuals are unless there is

00:08:25.400 --> 00:08:28.900
some mechanism specifically
built to make that happen.

00:08:28.900 --> 00:08:32.130
So looking at the idea of
moral rights in the context

00:08:32.130 --> 00:08:37.550
of this society today I would
say to have this balance

00:08:37.550 --> 00:08:40.660
between community and individual
is actually more important

00:08:40.660 --> 00:08:41.850
than ever.

00:08:41.850 --> 00:08:47.500
To have a really large
scale dissemination

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:51.040
of creativity the individual
creators have to be recognized.

00:08:51.040 --> 00:08:55.710
Alright? Somebody asked
why is the law necessary

00:08:55.710 --> 00:08:58.530
in the earlier panel.

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:02.050
To answer that I'll
give an experience.

00:09:02.050 --> 00:09:05.060
I've been consulting at a
startup for the past few months,

00:09:05.060 --> 00:09:07.680
almost a year now, and one
of the things I've learned is

00:09:07.680 --> 00:09:09.690
that nothing gets built

00:09:09.690 --> 00:09:14.470
at a startup unless it
is absolutely necessary

00:09:14.470 --> 00:09:16.000
for it to exist.

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:17.540
And the reasons that
it's necessary

00:09:17.540 --> 00:09:19.590
to exist are basically only two.

00:09:19.590 --> 00:09:21.120
It has to be a business
reason or it has

00:09:21.120 --> 00:09:23.110
to be a legal or
regulatory reason.

00:09:23.110 --> 00:09:27.400
It will not get built
because I want it to.

00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:30.090
There has to be some
affirmative reason

00:09:30.090 --> 00:09:33.040
that the tech community
has to do this.

00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:38.510
So that's my short
answer to that.

00:09:38.510 --> 00:09:42.040
For us attribution
that is our currency.

00:09:42.040 --> 00:09:44.480
I don't exist if people don't
know who I am and I mean

00:09:44.480 --> 00:09:48.560
that in the most literal
sense of I don't eat.

00:09:48.560 --> 00:09:53.030
So every time something goes
out that I've participated

00:09:53.030 --> 00:09:59.400
in that I don't get attribution
for it affects my family.

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:01.780
And how that affects
the community is

00:10:01.780 --> 00:10:04.910
that the less I am able to
create the less I'm able

00:10:04.910 --> 00:10:07.790
to help other people create.

00:10:07.790 --> 00:10:09.470
And the less the community of --

00:10:09.470 --> 00:10:12.140
, it shrinks the
community of artists

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:15.240
which will eventually
shrink the creativity

00:10:15.240 --> 00:10:16.000
of this country as a whole.

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:23.770
I don't have a watch on, I
don't know how I'm going here.

00:10:23.770 --> 00:10:24.080
Kimberely:

00:10:24.080 --> 00:10:24.900
&gt;&gt; One more minute.

00:10:24.900 --> 00:10:25.000
&gt;&gt; Melvin: Okay.

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:36.480
There is a bit of an
overlap between economic use

00:10:36.480 --> 00:10:40.330
and moral use, which I
guess we'll get into later.

00:10:40.330 --> 00:10:43.310
But I can speak as somebody
who was mentored by a lot

00:10:43.310 --> 00:10:46.140
of the older jazz
musicians in New York City

00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:48.460
that you cannot really
separate them.

00:10:48.460 --> 00:10:51.440
There are a lot of
things that --

00:10:51.440 --> 00:10:54.720
, attribution and
integrity are both important.

00:10:54.720 --> 00:10:58.270
And for us as musicians, it's
a slightly different issue

00:10:58.270 --> 00:11:00.830
because we are performers.

00:11:00.830 --> 00:11:02.150
It's not like in a book

00:11:02.150 --> 00:11:04.700
where you have one
version of the book.

00:11:04.700 --> 00:11:06.670
We play a song today, we'll
play it again tomorrow.

00:11:06.670 --> 00:11:08.860
Each performance is unique

00:11:10.290 --> 00:11:13.300
and each performance can
be disseminated on its own.

00:11:13.300 --> 00:11:15.130
So I think there's
a different --

00:11:15.130 --> 00:11:17.800
, there's room for a different
way of thinking about this idea

00:11:17.800 --> 00:11:22.340
that integrity will
somehow hinder the process

00:11:22.340 --> 00:11:23.580
of remix culture.

00:11:23.580 --> 00:11:26.370
I think that this is
something we'll examine further

00:11:26.370 --> 00:11:31.410
but I just wanted to
touch on that right now.

00:11:31.410 --> 00:11:34.710
&gt;&gt; Kimberely: Okay,
thank you Melvin.

00:11:34.710 --> 00:11:35.900
David Lowery.

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:38.810
&gt;&gt; David Lowery:
Thank you Melvin.

00:11:38.810 --> 00:11:45.690
You know about 23 years
ago I had a song released,

00:11:45.690 --> 00:11:49.590
and it started to
become popular on radio.

00:11:49.590 --> 00:11:53.800
One day I get a call from
the senior vice president

00:11:53.800 --> 00:11:58.980
of promotions at the record
label, and he basically says

00:11:58.980 --> 00:12:03.750
"that song, you know that song's
not about being stoned, right?"

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:06.700
[laughter] And I'm
like, "of course it's

00:12:06.700 --> 00:12:11.210
about being stoned Michael,"
but he kept saying it to me

00:12:11.210 --> 00:12:14.530
and then finally I was like,
"oh is there a problem?"

00:12:14.530 --> 00:12:17.870
He goes "yeah, I got this letter
I want you to sign and I need

00:12:17.870 --> 00:12:21.670
to fax it to a few
radio stations."

00:12:21.670 --> 00:12:25.260
So despite the fact
that I signed a letter

00:12:25.260 --> 00:12:30.110
that said the song "Low,"
which has a chorus "hey, hey,

00:12:30.110 --> 00:12:36.160
hey like being stoned"
[laughter] is

00:12:36.160 --> 00:12:37.220
about being stoned.

00:12:37.220 --> 00:12:39.350
Despite the fact that I
essentially signed a letter

00:12:39.350 --> 00:12:41.320
that said that it didn't, it is.

00:12:41.320 --> 00:12:45.310
And I guess in the world
of alternative rock

00:12:45.310 --> 00:12:49.610
and rock radio songs about
being stoned there are a couple

00:12:49.610 --> 00:12:55.160
of other people who have a few
tracks that basically come out

00:12:55.160 --> 00:13:00.230
and say that and one of
them of course is Tom Petty.

00:13:00.230 --> 00:13:06.940
So about the time that
we were first dealing

00:13:06.940 --> 00:13:13.320
with digital distribution-- at
first involuntarily by the likes

00:13:13.320 --> 00:13:17.040
of Napster and Kazaa and
Grokster and things like that--

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:21.550
somebody, probably because they
were stoned, mislabeled my song

00:13:21.550 --> 00:13:28.110
"Low" as being a Tom Petty song
called "Like Being Stoned .MP3"

00:13:28.110 --> 00:13:29.830
or "Tom Petty - Low -

00:13:29.830 --> 00:13:35.370
106" I guess 108 must
have been an MP3 disc

00:13:35.370 --> 00:13:37.810
that they ripped it from.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:46.080
And for the next six or seven
years I had this ongoing battle

00:13:46.080 --> 00:13:50.510
to kind of correct
this misrepresentation

00:13:50.510 --> 00:13:56.900
that that was actually a Tom
Petty song to the point where --

00:13:56.900 --> 00:14:02.060
, what's the name
of this website?

00:14:02.060 --> 00:14:03.750
And it's still out there.

00:14:03.750 --> 00:14:07.850
If you look it up on LastFM
it says it's a Tom Petty song.

00:14:09.420 --> 00:14:12.050
Picture of Tom Petty there.

00:14:12.050 --> 00:14:15.380
There's a Wikia called
misattributed

00:14:15.380 --> 00:14:20.630
and the Wikia misattributed song
that's one of the first examples

00:14:20.630 --> 00:14:24.510
of a song being misattributed
to artists.

00:14:24.510 --> 00:14:26.890
So you've got to
think about this.

00:14:26.890 --> 00:14:31.120
So my point, and I think
there's a lot of people here

00:14:31.120 --> 00:14:35.770
that feel the same way,
is that attribution,

00:14:35.770 --> 00:14:37.780
you can't really
separate attribution

00:14:37.780 --> 00:14:39.670
from the economic rights.

00:14:39.670 --> 00:14:42.700
I mean it's the same thing.

00:14:42.700 --> 00:14:45.640
Now we can decide what we
are going to do about that,

00:14:45.640 --> 00:14:50.420
because the last thing I want is
a DMCA loophole that can drive

00:14:50.420 --> 00:14:54.550
like a truck or several
thousand trucks through.

00:14:54.550 --> 00:15:03.580
But it is definitely -- , to
look at attribution as separate

00:15:03.580 --> 00:15:07.060
from an economic right is
ridiculous, because A) one,

00:15:07.060 --> 00:15:09.520
you know all those people are
freely downloading those songs,

00:15:09.520 --> 00:15:13.810
well maybe, maybe they would
have come to the concert,

00:15:13.810 --> 00:15:21.460
but they would have gone to a
Tom Petty concert [laughter].

00:15:21.460 --> 00:15:27.890
Also the fact is is when you're
a performer you know you build

00:15:27.890 --> 00:15:32.740
up a certain brand name on the
basis of your previous album

00:15:32.740 --> 00:15:34.460
so even before your album comes

00:15:34.460 --> 00:15:38.290
out it gets a value,
and economic value.

00:15:38.290 --> 00:15:41.840
Because it's going to be
based on the popularity

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:45.190
of the songs before that more
people are going to listen

00:15:45.190 --> 00:15:50.730
to it, maybe buy it,
get licensed in films.

00:15:50.730 --> 00:15:57.370
I mean it's really, it's silly
that it's not an economic right

00:15:57.370 --> 00:16:05.610
or that we would even think
that it's not an economic right.

00:16:05.610 --> 00:16:16.440
I guess the other thing is
that, I find there's a lot of --

00:16:16.440 --> 00:16:21.170
, you have this problem built
into our system for songwriters.

00:16:21.170 --> 00:16:23.060
Like my example is
a funny example

00:16:23.060 --> 00:16:24.900
as a performer, you know this.

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:31.400
But when you look at songwriters
they are almost never attributed

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:32.770
in the digital world.

00:16:32.770 --> 00:16:36.060
I mean I guess you
could dig around.

00:16:36.060 --> 00:16:43.130
I was using a popular
streaming service

00:16:43.130 --> 00:16:47.520
and they do have a lyrics
plug-in that you can load

00:16:47.520 --> 00:16:48.870
into the program
and then you click

00:16:48.870 --> 00:16:51.800
on lyrics for one of my songs.

00:16:51.800 --> 00:16:54.540
It was being performed
by another band

00:16:54.540 --> 00:16:57.070
but this was the song I wrote
and I looked at the lyrics

00:16:57.070 --> 00:16:59.360
and stuff and I was like
that's great, there's lyrics

00:16:59.360 --> 00:17:03.630
and that's attributed to the
wrong people as a writer.

00:17:03.630 --> 00:17:09.580
So I guess that's my point.

00:17:09.580 --> 00:17:15.930
It's an economic
issue, very strongly.

00:17:15.930 --> 00:17:18.070
&gt;&gt; Kimberely: Okay, thank you.

00:17:18.070 --> 00:17:21.150
Now to go to Yoko
to give us sort

00:17:21.150 --> 00:17:23.350
of the business perspective
on this.

00:17:23.350 --> 00:17:24.030
&gt;&gt; Yoko Miyashita:
You know it's great

00:17:24.030 --> 00:17:25.320
to follow Melvin and David.

00:17:25.320 --> 00:17:27.650
Thank you for that context
because it definitely touches

00:17:27.650 --> 00:17:30.320
on a number of things that
we see in my industry.

00:17:30.320 --> 00:17:32.460
So just a little
background on Getty Images.

00:17:32.460 --> 00:17:36.560
We represent close to 200,000
individual photographers as well

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:39.450
as having a staff of
150 staff photographers.

00:17:39.450 --> 00:17:42.840
So we are both stewards
and distributors

00:17:42.840 --> 00:17:45.340
of third-party content as
well as owners and generators

00:17:45.340 --> 00:17:49.200
of our own content.I
was thinking about this

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:51.470
as you were talking about these
issues, and I've been with Getty

00:17:51.470 --> 00:17:55.340
for about 11 years and I would
split those years as sort

00:17:55.340 --> 00:18:00.180
of pre-viral, pre-social
to the current state.

00:18:00.180 --> 00:18:03.380
And I would look at sort of
our activities particularly

00:18:03.380 --> 00:18:06.420
on the enforcement side as
seeing instances of uses

00:18:06.420 --> 00:18:10.740
and policing them, and
realizing with online platforms

00:18:10.740 --> 00:18:12.750
with the DMCA loopholes

00:18:12.750 --> 00:18:15.580
that that just simply
became untenable.

00:18:15.580 --> 00:18:19.820
So Getty took -- , really looked
at this as a business issue

00:18:19.820 --> 00:18:22.940
because when the genie
is out of the bottle

00:18:22.940 --> 00:18:25.040
on social media it's out.

00:18:25.040 --> 00:18:27.060
There is no stuffing it back in.

00:18:27.060 --> 00:18:32.240
And the big issue we encounter
here, particularly on images,

00:18:32.240 --> 00:18:35.250
is what I call the
right-click-copy-upload

00:18:35.250 --> 00:18:36.410
paradigm.

00:18:36.410 --> 00:18:40.540
When that happens, the metadata
that we have hired people

00:18:40.540 --> 00:18:43.170
to apply all of the
author's information,

00:18:43.170 --> 00:18:46.200
the copyright information,
all of those attributes

00:18:46.200 --> 00:18:49.550
that would ordinarily travel
with an image get stripped.

00:18:49.550 --> 00:18:50.540
So what happens?

00:18:50.540 --> 00:18:51.960
That image gets orphaned.

00:18:51.960 --> 00:18:53.470
That information
you would have had

00:18:53.470 --> 00:18:56.280
about that author not only
has that been infringed,

00:18:56.280 --> 00:19:00.710
not only has your economic
right there been messed with,

00:19:00.710 --> 00:19:03.370
it's now been disconnected
from the key information

00:19:03.370 --> 00:19:05.480
that tells you who
actually created that image,

00:19:05.480 --> 00:19:07.290
who is the author behind that.

00:19:07.290 --> 00:19:10.850
So it's an issue
that we have looked

00:19:10.850 --> 00:19:12.550
at from a business
perspective and said,

00:19:12.550 --> 00:19:13.970
"all right this is happening."

00:19:13.970 --> 00:19:18.020
You can send all the
takedown notices in the world,

00:19:18.020 --> 00:19:20.570
and you will never
solve this issue.

00:19:20.570 --> 00:19:24.560
So what have we done as a
company is really looked at ways

00:19:24.560 --> 00:19:28.530
of distributing content to
actually bring attribution back.

00:19:28.530 --> 00:19:34.380
How do you leverage this innate
human need to share images?

00:19:34.380 --> 00:19:37.910
Well you do that
by offering embed.

00:19:37.910 --> 00:19:42.260
In May 2014, we launched an
offering through our website

00:19:42.260 --> 00:19:46.580
for free embed use for
noncommercial purposes.

00:19:46.580 --> 00:19:50.820
We hai spent years pursuing
these small nonprofit

00:19:50.820 --> 00:19:53.210
organization school
projects and really

00:19:53.210 --> 00:19:55.510
that is a terrible PR campaign.

00:19:55.510 --> 00:19:58.490
Really whacking the
schoolteachers over the head

00:19:58.490 --> 00:20:02.170
with a C&amp;D and a
lawsuit or demand

00:20:02.170 --> 00:20:06.480
for payment really not great for
company PR, not great for us.

00:20:06.480 --> 00:20:07.220
So what did we say?

00:20:07.220 --> 00:20:09.400
We opened up 90 plus
percent of our collections,

00:20:09.400 --> 00:20:11.100
and said if you want
to use our content

00:20:11.100 --> 00:20:12.510
for noncommercial use great.

00:20:12.510 --> 00:20:15.090
Here's our embed and
what does it too?

00:20:15.090 --> 00:20:19.330
It includes a small watermark
as well as attribution.

00:20:19.330 --> 00:20:21.810
Give the creators credit
for what they've done.

00:20:21.810 --> 00:20:23.590
And it also links
back to our site,

00:20:23.590 --> 00:20:27.340
so if someone actually likes
that picture they can go

00:20:27.340 --> 00:20:30.150
through then, make their way
back to the Getty Images site,

00:20:30.150 --> 00:20:35.260
explore more images by a
particular photographer.

00:20:35.260 --> 00:20:38.370
Soon after embed we've
launched social sharing.

00:20:38.370 --> 00:20:40.660
So if you now go to the
Getty Images website

00:20:40.660 --> 00:20:43.310
and see a picture you like
we encourage you to share it

00:20:43.310 --> 00:20:45.540
but it will be shared
with attribution,

00:20:45.540 --> 00:20:49.840
a link back wherever
those platforms allow us.

00:20:49.840 --> 00:20:50.870
So you do again --

00:20:50.870 --> 00:20:54.600
, can correlate that back to
the person who created it.

00:20:54.600 --> 00:20:57.020
I'm not saying this
is the ideal solution

00:20:57.020 --> 00:21:00.430
but this is the solution that
we currently have in the context

00:21:00.430 --> 00:21:03.880
of where the legal
framework stands.

00:21:03.880 --> 00:21:06.420
If it's going to be shared
we want it to be shared

00:21:06.420 --> 00:21:10.260
with attribution, with a
possible potential for people

00:21:10.260 --> 00:21:12.000
to find more images
from these creators.

00:21:25.040 --> 00:21:27.410
The other, you know the
other thing that one

00:21:27.410 --> 00:21:32.650
of our affiliates, Getty Images
acquired a technology in 2011.

00:21:32.650 --> 00:21:35.010
It was the frontrunner in
image recognition software.

00:21:35.010 --> 00:21:37.040
They do digital fingerprinting

00:21:37.040 --> 00:21:39.150
and essentially help you
identify images on the internet.

00:21:39.150 --> 00:21:40.840
You can see the obvious
use cases

00:21:40.840 --> 00:21:42.940
for pursuing infringements.

00:21:42.940 --> 00:21:45.040
But what we've done is
really collected one

00:21:45.040 --> 00:21:48.360
of the largest indices
of online imagery.

00:21:48.360 --> 00:21:50.470
So a fantastic solution
for orphan works,

00:21:50.470 --> 00:21:52.510
but also just an open API.

00:21:52.510 --> 00:21:55.660
So the technology is out
there to help platforms,

00:21:55.660 --> 00:21:58.910
to help companies, to help
anyone who is looking figure

00:21:58.910 --> 00:22:01.010
out who actually
created an image,

00:22:01.010 --> 00:22:03.070
who actually owns the copyright,

00:22:03.070 --> 00:22:05.130
where it's available
for licensing.

00:22:05.130 --> 00:22:06.630
This technology exists.

00:22:06.630 --> 00:22:07.610
It's out there.

00:22:07.610 --> 00:22:08.900
We offer it.

00:22:08.900 --> 00:22:14.110
But there needs to be an impetus
to drive uptake of these kinds

00:22:14.110 --> 00:22:15.810
of available technologies.

00:22:15.810 --> 00:22:17.210
We know they exist.

00:22:17.210 --> 00:22:21.610
They are underutilized across
the industry but again,

00:22:21.610 --> 00:22:25.010
that is a process to
reattach this attribution,

00:22:25.010 --> 00:22:27.510
to reattach the metadata,
to reattach all

00:22:27.510 --> 00:22:29.700
of these key attributes
that go directly

00:22:29.700 --> 00:22:32.750
into the economic
viability of creative works.

00:22:32.750 --> 00:22:38.180
I wanted to touch on a point you
made, David, about to have --

00:22:38.180 --> 00:22:42.200
, it's not just knowing who the
author is so you can search.

00:22:42.200 --> 00:22:45.650
This is all driven in the
platform space by algorithms.

00:22:45.650 --> 00:22:48.330
If your name is not
showing up with that song

00:22:48.330 --> 00:22:50.230
and is not being
attributed to you,

00:22:50.230 --> 00:22:52.530
everything else that's
driving the algorithms

00:22:52.530 --> 00:22:54.780
that will drive traffic
back to you or discovery

00:22:54.780 --> 00:22:58.260
of your content, those
connections are being cut off.

00:22:58.260 --> 00:23:01.440
So I do see these as
absolutely interrelated

00:23:01.440 --> 00:23:03.470
and you cannot separate the two.

00:23:03.470 --> 00:23:08.340
I think that's really it for me.

00:23:08.340 --> 00:23:08.630
Thank you.

