00:25:05.310 --> 00:25:07.570
Why? Well because if you
talk to a bunch of creators,

00:25:07.570 --> 00:25:10.420
and now Melvin and David will
correct me quickly on this,

00:25:10.420 --> 00:25:12.900
but I don't think, you
guys don't write songs just

00:25:12.900 --> 00:25:15.480
because there's copyright,
you don't create --

00:25:15.480 --> 00:25:17.810
, well maybe you
do, I don't know.

00:25:17.810 --> 00:25:20.250
So in other words if you say
oh my gosh I am not going

00:25:20.250 --> 00:25:24.060
to become a songwriter if
there were not copyright?

00:25:24.060 --> 00:25:26.680
&gt;&gt; David: Yeah but I don't think
you do album eight or nine.

00:25:26.680 --> 00:25:27.210
&gt;&gt; Sean: True, right [laughter],

00:25:27.210 --> 00:25:30.380
so there's a role
for it, exactly.

00:25:30.380 --> 00:25:33.670
And then the question becomes
how do you get it all financed?

00:25:33.670 --> 00:25:35.280
But the point here
is that I think a lot

00:25:35.280 --> 00:25:39.490
of people now realize that is
copyright as only an incentive

00:25:39.490 --> 00:25:41.720
to create probably doesn't
tell the whole story.

00:25:41.720 --> 00:25:44.750
It's a big part of the story
but it's not the complete story.

00:25:44.750 --> 00:25:46.080
And so if you look
at the history

00:25:46.080 --> 00:25:50.450
of the term publication
going back to Roman period

00:25:50.450 --> 00:25:53.340
"publicari," it was
making a public commitment.

00:25:53.340 --> 00:25:56.050
And so what I think has
become invisible to us

00:25:56.050 --> 00:25:59.290
in the social media age
where people blur the line

00:25:59.290 --> 00:26:00.510
between public and private.

00:26:00.510 --> 00:26:01.900
We tweet everything out.

00:26:01.900 --> 00:26:03.020
We Instagram everything out.

00:26:03.020 --> 00:26:04.500
Snapchat everything out.

00:26:04.500 --> 00:26:07.690
But think about if you are
a creator, and this is true

00:26:07.690 --> 00:26:11.010
for a creative artists and
even for us wonky academics,

00:26:11.010 --> 00:26:13.790
when you finally say, and I'm
looking at the journal students

00:26:13.790 --> 00:26:15.900
over there, okay you guys, and
I have stuff I've published

00:26:15.900 --> 00:26:18.390
with them, they always
send me, "is it final?

00:26:18.390 --> 00:26:19.890
Are you going to
give us the sign off?

00:26:19.890 --> 00:26:21.700
Can we release, can
we publish this now?"

00:26:21.700 --> 00:26:24.740
That's a fraught moment
because if I say something wrong

00:26:24.740 --> 00:26:27.720
in there, I didn't catch a
typo, it comes back to haunt me.

00:26:27.720 --> 00:26:30.010
And so now on the performance
side, on the improv side,

00:26:30.010 --> 00:26:34.170
sometimes the rough edges around
it can be exactly what you want.

00:26:34.170 --> 00:26:38.850
But in the finished artifact
side it's often not what

00:26:38.850 --> 00:26:39.150
you want.

00:26:39.150 --> 00:26:41.090
You're trying to get a
very particular thing.

00:26:41.090 --> 00:26:43.660
So what does this
mean for moral rights?

00:26:43.660 --> 00:26:47.510
Well, first moral rights is
important because we angst a lot

00:26:47.510 --> 00:26:49.910
about is it good
enough to be published,

00:26:49.910 --> 00:26:51.470
to be publicly released?

00:26:51.470 --> 00:26:53.630
And second, without
getting too maudlin,

00:26:53.630 --> 00:26:56.490
but in the world we live
in today you have a lot

00:26:56.490 --> 00:26:59.740
of potential risk and liability
for things you publicly put

00:26:59.740 --> 00:27:01.450
out there as creators.

00:27:01.450 --> 00:27:04.070
We don't have to give specific
examples, but just think

00:27:04.070 --> 00:27:06.540
about that in the world today.

00:27:06.540 --> 00:27:08.260
And so the notion of integrity.

00:27:08.260 --> 00:27:10.630
What if somebody takes
my carefully constructed

00:27:10.630 --> 00:27:12.990
"here's what I really
meant to put out there"

00:27:12.990 --> 00:27:16.210
and they change it and
my name is still on it?

00:27:16.210 --> 00:27:19.500
And now suddenly that could get
me just professional problems,

00:27:19.500 --> 00:27:22.370
or it could get me physical
harm kind of problems.

00:27:22.370 --> 00:27:25.010
Can't I then get my
name taken off it?

00:27:25.010 --> 00:27:27.120
Or can't I just withdraw
the work entirely

00:27:27.120 --> 00:27:29.050
if I realize that's
not what I want

00:27:29.050 --> 00:27:31.170
to publicly commit to anymore?

00:27:31.170 --> 00:27:32.410
Okay, so that's my main point.

00:27:32.410 --> 00:27:33.940
Second point is that I think,

00:27:33.940 --> 00:27:36.310
and I like that Professor
Ginsberg was starting to open

00:27:36.310 --> 00:27:38.750
up that door and talk
about work-made-for-hire,

00:27:38.750 --> 00:27:40.030
because that's going
to be I think one

00:27:40.030 --> 00:27:42.850
of the biggest problems
for meshing in or bringing

00:27:42.850 --> 00:27:45.990
in a full moral right system
into the U.S. copyright system.

00:27:45.990 --> 00:27:49.220
Our work made for hire is
based on the economic basis

00:27:49.220 --> 00:27:50.780
of our copyright system,

00:27:50.780 --> 00:27:54.180
so it means the economic
employer can be the author

00:27:54.180 --> 00:27:57.800
for purposes of copyright
statute.

00:27:57.800 --> 00:28:00.180
But there's another sense
of work-made-for-hire

00:28:00.180 --> 00:28:01.650
where you have -- ,
and this goes back

00:28:01.650 --> 00:28:04.500
to actually continental
precedents going back

00:28:04.500 --> 00:28:07.300
into the Renaissance period
where you have the great artiste

00:28:07.300 --> 00:28:09.710
who directs people
and usually then his,

00:28:09.710 --> 00:28:12.690
but it could be her studio,
and they actually implement.

00:28:12.690 --> 00:28:14.790
They execute on things.

00:28:14.790 --> 00:28:17.500
So you know we know the
case is about how you decide

00:28:17.500 --> 00:28:19.640
who is an author and who
is not but that's going

00:28:19.640 --> 00:28:22.280
to become I think incredibly
important as you think

00:28:22.280 --> 00:28:24.440
about then bringing in a
fuller moral right system

00:28:24.440 --> 00:28:26.140
if that's something
you want to do.

00:28:26.140 --> 00:28:30.720
With that I'll turn
it over to Scott.

00:28:30.720 --> 00:28:30.840
&gt;&gt; Scott Turow: Great.

00:28:30.840 --> 00:28:33.520
Well thank you all.

00:28:33.520 --> 00:28:38.830
My acquaintance with moral
rights began what is now a long

00:28:38.830 --> 00:28:48.020
time ago when I was thrilled to
get a draft of a movie contract

00:28:48.020 --> 00:28:52.150
for the rights to "Presumed
Innocent" and my life had gone

00:28:52.150 --> 00:28:54.660
through an extraordinary
transformation.

00:28:54.660 --> 00:28:56.950
I had written "Presumed
Innocent"

00:28:56.950 --> 00:29:00.100
on the morning commuter train
and finished it in my basement

00:29:00.100 --> 00:29:07.290
and all of a sudden, literally,
I was that proverbial person

00:29:07.290 --> 00:29:10.650
in the creative world who
gets struck by lightning.

00:29:10.650 --> 00:29:14.380
And in the process
the movie rights

00:29:14.380 --> 00:29:16.730
to the book were purchased.

00:29:16.730 --> 00:29:20.450
A draft contract arrives
and of course it says

00:29:20.450 --> 00:29:25.440
that among the rights I
am selling are my right

00:29:25.440 --> 00:29:28.830
to make a claim based
on droit morale,

00:29:28.830 --> 00:29:31.040
and I'm sure people are
fainting all over the room

00:29:31.040 --> 00:29:37.110
of my French accent
[laughter], or moral rights.

00:29:37.110 --> 00:29:39.180
So I called my lawyer
and I said,

00:29:39.180 --> 00:29:40.690
"well what are moral rights?"

00:29:40.690 --> 00:29:42.340
And he said, "well it
has got nothing to do

00:29:42.340 --> 00:29:43.510
with you, you're an American."

00:29:43.510 --> 00:29:50.050
[ Laughter ]

00:29:50.050 --> 00:29:52.510
But I've always been
conscious of the concept just

00:29:52.510 --> 00:29:54.570
because I've been
through law school.

00:29:54.570 --> 00:30:00.680
I never took a copyright
class, but the notion just

00:30:00.680 --> 00:30:03.020
because of the term
appeal to me.

00:30:03.020 --> 00:30:09.410
And there is -- , we recognize
creative work as standing

00:30:09.410 --> 00:30:14.810
on some kind of different
platform than other products

00:30:14.810 --> 00:30:18.360
in the marketplace,
because of the intimacy

00:30:18.360 --> 00:30:20.010
of the creative act.

00:30:20.010 --> 00:30:25.970
And for lack of any other term,

00:30:25.970 --> 00:30:28.970
artists traditionally
are believed

00:30:28.970 --> 00:30:31.640
to have put a little
bit of their soul

00:30:31.640 --> 00:30:35.620
into whatever they create,
whether it's what they paint

00:30:35.620 --> 00:30:39.410
or the songs they compose,
the sculptures they make

00:30:39.410 --> 00:30:49.060
or for artists and authors the
productions that come from them.

00:30:49.060 --> 00:30:54.240
And I think we do have the right
to assert that there is a kind

00:30:54.240 --> 00:30:58.790
of specialness in creative
work and that is recognized

00:30:58.790 --> 00:31:03.670
in terms of moral rights.

00:31:03.670 --> 00:31:05.900
Everybody here has
talked generally

00:31:05.900 --> 00:31:08.490
about the right of attribution.

00:31:08.490 --> 00:31:13.760
I sit here on what is a sad
day for the Authors Guild

00:31:13.760 --> 00:31:16.390
of which I was once president.

00:31:16.390 --> 00:31:19.820
Our long-running
fight with Google

00:31:19.820 --> 00:31:25.490
over the Google Books project
is officially over today.

00:31:25.490 --> 00:31:29.540
The Supreme Court refused
to grant cert in the case.

00:31:29.540 --> 00:31:33.320
And I doubt there are
any people in the room

00:31:33.320 --> 00:31:37.480
who need a long-winded
explanation of what was involved

00:31:37.480 --> 00:31:40.690
in the Google Books case.

00:31:40.690 --> 00:31:45.650
And it's certainly true
that our opposition was

00:31:45.650 --> 00:31:47.220
fundamentally economic.

00:31:47.220 --> 00:31:50.890
The notion that a large
corporate entity could decide

00:31:50.890 --> 00:31:55.280
on its own to take and
copy an authors work,

00:31:55.280 --> 00:32:00.680
not change a single word of
it, offer no new expression

00:32:00.680 --> 00:32:04.990
and still make the
entire work available

00:32:04.990 --> 00:32:08.570
through selective display

00:32:08.570 --> 00:32:13.640
of so-called snippets
seemed fundamentally wrong.

00:32:13.640 --> 00:32:16.840
But we've lost that fight.

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:25.140
But the moral rights issues
still remain in that discussion.

00:32:25.140 --> 00:32:28.540
And just by way of example,

00:32:28.540 --> 00:32:30.960
at one point we had reached
a settlement with Google

00:32:30.960 --> 00:32:34.360
which was one of
those situations

00:32:34.360 --> 00:32:36.020
where the Justice
Department came in

00:32:36.020 --> 00:32:38.500
and disagreed with both sides.

00:32:38.500 --> 00:32:42.330
And I still, of course, disagree

00:32:42.330 --> 00:32:45.010
with the Justice
Department about this.

00:32:45.010 --> 00:32:49.650
But we found in our own
membership substantial

00:32:49.650 --> 00:32:52.230
opposition to the settlement.

00:32:52.230 --> 00:32:57.580
Not overriding, and what
were they objecting to?

00:32:57.580 --> 00:33:03.300
They believed, they didn't like
the idea of Google coming in

00:33:03.300 --> 00:33:05.240
and just taking their work.

00:33:05.240 --> 00:33:08.460
They didn't want it
displayed on Google.

00:33:08.460 --> 00:33:10.840
And even though we
argued that the settlement

00:33:10.840 --> 00:33:13.890
in fact would give them
the right to opt out

00:33:13.890 --> 00:33:15.630
and withdraw their work,

00:33:15.630 --> 00:33:19.330
they found it fundamentally
offensive.

00:33:19.330 --> 00:33:23.350
Now songwriters don't
exist in that world.

00:33:23.350 --> 00:33:26.250
They have a compulsory
licensing system.

00:33:26.250 --> 00:33:31.960
Other people of course,
objected to Google books

00:33:31.960 --> 00:33:34.490
because of the right
of integrity.

00:33:34.490 --> 00:33:36.860
They didn't like the idea

00:33:36.860 --> 00:33:42.640
that there was this robot
being created that would deal

00:33:42.640 --> 00:33:46.190
with their books selectively

00:33:46.190 --> 00:33:50.330
and choose snippets
based on certain words.

00:33:50.330 --> 00:33:53.610
And certainly the right
to control publication

00:33:53.610 --> 00:33:57.250
of your work is implicated
in this kind

00:33:57.250 --> 00:34:00.020
of wholesale use and display.

00:34:00.020 --> 00:34:05.870
Rights of attribution of course
are important to authors too.

00:34:05.870 --> 00:34:08.760
It's rare to steal
an entire novel

00:34:08.760 --> 00:34:12.660
and have somebody put
his or her name on it.

00:34:12.660 --> 00:34:19.520
But poets and essayists are in
this world of rampant plagiarism

00:34:19.520 --> 00:34:23.390
of course, often
exposed to that.

00:34:23.390 --> 00:34:27.270
But all of these
concepts seem to me

00:34:27.270 --> 00:34:32.080
to remain very much
relevant to the discussion

00:34:32.080 --> 00:34:35.560
of the author's place
in the world, too.

00:34:35.560 --> 00:34:37.800
&gt;&gt;Kimberley: Okay, thank you.

