The idea was you
create something,

00:43:26.220 --> 00:43:28.860
you can control it
completely until it is ready

00:43:28.860 --> 00:43:31.640
to be released because,
thank you Melvin,

00:43:31.640 --> 00:43:35.080
and perhaps David agrees too,
it's very personal and until

00:43:35.080 --> 00:43:40.120
that thing is ready you do
not want it getting out there.

00:43:40.120 --> 00:43:42.510
&gt;&gt; Kimberely: So I actually
have a question for Yoko.

00:43:42.510 --> 00:43:45.530
Are these types of issues
ones that are important

00:43:45.530 --> 00:43:48.760
to the photographers that
Getty Images works with?

00:43:48.760 --> 00:43:55.420
Do you help them enforce rights
of attribution in addition to,

00:43:55.420 --> 00:43:59.960
obviously, the initiatives that
Getty has come up with to try

00:43:59.960 --> 00:44:03.370
to embed and provide for social
sharing, but are these types

00:44:03.370 --> 00:44:07.520
of concerns like "I really don't
want my photograph appearing

00:44:07.520 --> 00:44:10.680
on this type of website or
in this type of concept."?

00:44:10.680 --> 00:44:12.730
&gt;&gt; Yoko: The integrity
issues are really interesting

00:44:12.730 --> 00:44:15.650
particularly because we really
sit and broker the relationship

00:44:15.650 --> 00:44:18.950
between the artists and
essentially the people licensing

00:44:18.950 --> 00:44:20.500
or purchasing content.

00:44:20.500 --> 00:44:23.570
And we handle it contractually,
as you would imagine,

00:44:23.570 --> 00:44:25.970
but the stock photography
industry is built

00:44:25.970 --> 00:44:28.950
on "somebody takes your
picture and customizes it

00:44:28.950 --> 00:44:31.180
and modifies it and
uses it in a way

00:44:31.180 --> 00:44:34.180
that suits their particular
need" eliminating the need

00:44:34.180 --> 00:44:36.120
to shoot custom content.

00:44:36.120 --> 00:44:42.020
But what comes with that is
obviously these absolutely human

00:44:42.020 --> 00:44:46.840
personal decisions and opinions
and thoughts about what is

00:44:46.840 --> 00:44:47.940
and is not acceptable.

00:44:47.940 --> 00:44:50.930
We're pretty clear about
those conversations

00:44:50.930 --> 00:44:52.600
with our contributing
photographers

00:44:52.600 --> 00:44:55.670
around you know we asked
you really aren't able

00:44:55.670 --> 00:45:00.150
to exercise your moral rights
with respect to particular uses.

00:45:00.150 --> 00:45:02.320
Yes, we have mechanisms
to say okay no use

00:45:02.320 --> 00:45:04.820
in tobacco, no use in alcohol.

00:45:04.820 --> 00:45:08.070
We have the ability and the
means to honor those types

00:45:08.070 --> 00:45:10.300
of restrictions but
once you really put it

00:45:10.300 --> 00:45:12.090
out into the distribution sort

00:45:12.090 --> 00:45:17.890
of ecosystem there is
this understood exchange,

00:45:17.890 --> 00:45:22.110
a contractual exchange around
what you can or can't control.

00:45:22.110 --> 00:45:25.870
And notwithstanding sort of an
open dialogue and transparency

00:45:25.870 --> 00:45:28.820
about that you just never know
what's really going to hit you

00:45:28.820 --> 00:45:29.770
and what's quite personal.

00:45:29.770 --> 00:45:31.860
And we've seen some really
interesting issues come up,

00:45:31.860 --> 00:45:34.670
and we do have to deal with
those on a one-off basis and try

00:45:34.670 --> 00:45:35.660
to find that middle ground.

00:45:35.660 --> 00:45:36.550
And sometimes that means

00:45:36.550 --> 00:45:38.750
that photographer
wants to pull content.

00:45:38.750 --> 00:45:41.600
But if a campaign is
run, a campaign is run.

00:45:41.600 --> 00:45:44.030
So you do see those
and we do sort of stand

00:45:44.030 --> 00:45:45.040
in the middle again trying

00:45:45.040 --> 00:45:49.030
to broker what is the best
solution for each side here.

00:45:49.030 --> 00:45:51.850
And I think it's really --

00:45:51.850 --> 00:45:55.670
, people are so creative you
just can never know what they're

00:45:55.670 --> 00:45:59.370
going to come out with, and
it may be absolutely offensive

00:45:59.370 --> 00:46:00.910
to some, it may not be.

00:46:00.910 --> 00:46:04.760
I mean it is sort of what
makes it interesting.

00:46:04.760 --> 00:46:08.080
But again to that
private/public, we just sort

00:46:08.080 --> 00:46:10.880
of wait in the middle
and see what happens.

00:46:10.880 --> 00:46:12.510
But what I'll go back

00:46:12.510 --> 00:46:15.650
to is really I do think
technology has solutions

00:46:15.650 --> 00:46:19.880
to offer in the space that have
yet to be really fully explored.

00:46:19.880 --> 00:46:23.550
And when we talk about
control and when I think

00:46:23.550 --> 00:46:27.030
about online it really
truly is the reflection

00:46:27.030 --> 00:46:32.800
of those control mechanisms
within the 1s and 0s.

00:46:32.800 --> 00:46:37.340
So I'm not sure that
answers that question, Kim.

00:46:37.340 --> 00:46:41.180
&gt;&gt; Kimberley: So does anyone
else on the panel have thoughts

00:46:41.180 --> 00:46:48.710
about sort of ways to manage
these issues about solutions,

00:46:48.710 --> 00:46:53.880
or is it just a problem that
is inherent in the nature

00:46:53.880 --> 00:46:56.700
of internet distribution?

00:46:58.990 --> 00:47:01.690
&gt;&gt; David: Well I mean I feel

00:47:01.690 --> 00:47:06.990
like sometimes we frame
the whole question wrong.

00:47:06.990 --> 00:47:10.990
Like we are sort of worrying
about the rights of like a group

00:47:10.990 --> 00:47:18.710
of consumers or an industry
or a preferred technology.

00:47:18.710 --> 00:47:23.570
But rights only vest
in the individual.

00:47:23.570 --> 00:47:29.830
And I don't think me asserting
my rights if it breaks

00:47:29.830 --> 00:47:32.240
or wrecks a certain technology,

00:47:32.240 --> 00:47:35.390
then it wasn't a good enough
technology in the first place

00:47:35.390 --> 00:47:36.140
and it should die [laughter].

00:47:36.140 --> 00:47:41.860
I mean think about what we lose?

00:47:41.860 --> 00:47:46.480
How did we get this turned
around so backwards that we have

00:47:46.480 --> 00:47:50.570
to pick winners and losers
in the technology world?

00:47:50.570 --> 00:47:56.240
If the internet is the most
wonderful thing ever it should

00:47:56.240 --> 00:48:00.580
be able to withstand me
asserting my moral rights.

00:48:00.580 --> 00:48:01.920
Right?

00:48:03.570 --> 00:48:07.820
&gt;&gt;Melvin: Well I mean the thing
I always say is that this idea

00:48:07.820 --> 00:48:12.830
that information should be
free theoretically also applies

00:48:12.830 --> 00:48:14.980
to your bank information.

00:48:14.980 --> 00:48:17.070
But nobody has any problem

00:48:17.070 --> 00:48:19.610
with having their bank
information locked down.

00:48:19.610 --> 00:48:23.400
So it becomes a question
of what --

00:48:23.400 --> 00:48:26.420
, going back to what I said
earlier what people want

00:48:26.420 --> 00:48:31.020
to build and what
people need to build.

00:48:31.020 --> 00:48:36.950
It's not theoretically
as Yoko said earlier,

00:48:36.950 --> 00:48:40.620
I mean her pictures go
up with the metadata on

00:48:40.620 --> 00:48:45.150
and then magically the
metadata disappears so the fact

00:48:45.150 --> 00:48:51.240
that that happens is because
there was nothing built -

00:48:51.240 --> 00:48:52.360
&gt;&gt; Yoko: We allowed
it to happen -

00:48:52.360 --> 00:48:54.740
&gt;&gt; Melvin: To allow
it to remain.

00:48:54.740 --> 00:48:56.260
Or you know I don't want
to put it the other way

00:48:56.260 --> 00:48:58.640
but you know the
implication is there.

00:48:58.640 --> 00:49:01.700
So I think as I said earlier
there are going to have

00:49:01.700 --> 00:49:06.570
to be some affirmative
forcing of people's hands

00:49:06.570 --> 00:49:09.460
to enforce community,
unfortunately.

00:49:09.460 --> 00:49:11.280
Because people are just
going to build according

00:49:11.280 --> 00:49:13.570
to what they can get
away with building.

00:49:13.570 --> 00:49:15.070
&gt;&gt; Kimberely: So Scott
you've been kind of quiet.

00:49:15.070 --> 00:49:16.990
Do you have any concluding
thoughts before we go

00:49:16.990 --> 00:49:19.830
to audience questions?

00:49:19.830 --> 00:49:23.200
&gt;&gt; Scott: Again I'm sitting
here thinking about all

00:49:23.200 --> 00:49:27.200
of these issues as they apply
to authors, and of course,

00:49:27.200 --> 00:49:36.470
you know our problems have
to do with theft, piracy,

00:49:36.470 --> 00:49:40.430
which is I'm sure a
problem across the board.

00:49:40.430 --> 00:49:45.860
And I'm also thinking
about the fact

00:49:45.860 --> 00:49:50.910
that it would probably
behoove us, those who try

00:49:50.910 --> 00:49:57.260
to be author's representatives
as well as authors,

00:49:57.260 --> 00:50:01.520
to explain this in
the personal terms,

00:50:01.520 --> 00:50:04.660
which I think moral
rights implicate

00:50:04.660 --> 00:50:07.880
and the way Melvin's
been talking about it,

00:50:07.880 --> 00:50:11.640
that you know yes it's property.

00:50:11.640 --> 00:50:15.660
You're stealing property
but it's property plus.

00:50:15.660 --> 00:50:20.770
Creative work always has been
and moral rights recognizes

00:50:20.770 --> 00:50:27.360
that plus aspect
to creative work.

00:50:27.360 --> 00:50:29.580
And I think it's important

00:50:29.580 --> 00:50:35.520
because it's not
just being ripped off

00:50:35.520 --> 00:50:42.140
by the pirate it's the personal
insult that goes with it.

00:50:42.140 --> 00:50:44.220
Because look my books
are in the library.

00:50:44.220 --> 00:50:48.440
People can go read them
for free, and I love that.

00:50:48.440 --> 00:50:52.540
But that's because I chose
to participate in that system

00:50:52.540 --> 00:50:56.300
and I didn't choose to
participate in a system

00:50:56.300 --> 00:51:02.330
where somebody else is going
to take control of my work.

00:51:02.330 --> 00:51:05.760
&gt;&gt; Kimberely: Okay so
we have about 10 minutes

00:51:05.760 --> 00:51:07.990
for audience questions.

00:51:07.990 --> 00:51:11.700
&gt;&gt; Audience: I have
a question for Scott.

00:51:11.700 --> 00:51:13.490
How do you feel about
fan fiction?

00:51:13.490 --> 00:51:23.710
&gt;&gt; Scott: You know I think it's
pretty interesting, personally,

00:51:23.710 --> 00:51:29.860
and you know you can't
deal with this globally.

00:51:29.860 --> 00:51:34.350
It depends on exactly
what is being done

00:51:34.350 --> 00:51:39.600
and what exactly is being
appropriated and then what kind

00:51:39.600 --> 00:51:41.820
of use gets made of it.

00:51:41.820 --> 00:51:50.100
But what I like about the
moral rights discussion is

00:51:50.100 --> 00:51:53.770
that it involves us

00:51:53.770 --> 00:51:59.010
in discussing the spiritual
element of creative work.

00:51:59.010 --> 00:52:01.640
I know when I write
something that it's going

00:52:01.640 --> 00:52:07.090
to be meaningful, I hope, to an
audience and that they are going

00:52:07.090 --> 00:52:10.650
to take it in and make use

00:52:10.650 --> 00:52:14.580
of that imaginative
experience in their own way.

00:52:14.580 --> 00:52:20.610
So fan fiction is
part of that process.

00:52:20.610 --> 00:52:27.750
Again, it's complicated and it
becomes particularly complicated

00:52:27.750 --> 00:52:34.330
if somebody is trying to make
economic use of something

00:52:34.330 --> 00:52:36.460
that I want to control.

00:52:36.460 --> 00:52:47.420
But you know the notion of it
it actually does appeal to me.

00:52:47.420 --> 00:52:49.920
&gt;&gt; Melvin: I want
to just kind of tag

00:52:49.920 --> 00:52:51.530
onto Scott's comments
a little bit.

00:52:51.530 --> 00:52:54.750
I mean it seems people
have to remember

00:52:54.750 --> 00:52:58.240
that we all started
off learning,

00:52:58.240 --> 00:53:02.300
and we all started off
copying other people.

00:53:02.300 --> 00:53:06.720
Creative people in general
are not against emulation.

00:53:06.720 --> 00:53:07.800
We're not against remix.

00:53:07.800 --> 00:53:08.820
We're not against any of that.

00:53:08.820 --> 00:53:14.180
What we are against is this
distance that's been put

00:53:14.180 --> 00:53:17.090
in between us and the
community of people

00:53:17.090 --> 00:53:19.280
who would want to emulate us.

00:53:19.280 --> 00:53:21.860
You know it's like the person
who told me how to play bass,

00:53:21.860 --> 00:53:24.820
I learned, I was copying
him but then I was going

00:53:24.820 --> 00:53:26.310
to his house every week.

00:53:26.310 --> 00:53:31.340
The people that I was
listening to their records,

00:53:31.340 --> 00:53:35.400
there was a relationship beyond
just okay there's a website

00:53:35.400 --> 00:53:38.000
and the website is
scraping my data.

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:41.540
And I think that
to solve that is--

00:53:41.540 --> 00:53:42.990
we kind of have to go backwards.

00:53:42.990 --> 00:53:46.060
And that's why I think the moral
rights conversation is actually

00:53:46.060 --> 00:53:50.240
applicable in this era.

00:53:50.240 --> 00:53:52.480
&gt;&gt; Audience: Question
for David and Melvin,

00:53:52.480 --> 00:53:55.910
as I'm sure you know Section 115
of the Copyright Act provides

00:53:55.910 --> 00:53:58.840
for a compulsory license that
once you've written a song

00:53:58.840 --> 00:54:01.970
that anyone else without
your permission can go ahead

00:54:01.970 --> 00:54:04.170
and record a cover version.

00:54:04.170 --> 00:54:05.680
Do you like that?

00:54:05.680 --> 00:54:06.230
Does it bother you?

00:54:06.230 --> 00:54:08.690
Do you think it bothers
most songwriters, composers?

00:54:08.690 --> 00:54:10.490
&gt;&gt; Melvin: We are about to
go all Worldwide Wrestling

00:54:10.490 --> 00:54:14.620
Federation with me
and [laughter].

00:54:14.620 --> 00:54:23.080
It's two things that
don't go together.

00:54:23.080 --> 00:54:26.070
I mean I am of two
minds over this.

00:54:26.070 --> 00:54:30.880
I mean our organization
is pro-compulsory license.

00:54:30.880 --> 00:54:34.210
The reason we are
pro-compulsory license--

00:54:34.210 --> 00:54:36.520
but there is a very
strong caveat with that,

00:54:36.520 --> 00:54:41.140
which is from our and the
issue is that there has

00:54:41.140 --> 00:54:46.350
to be fair market
rate paid when a piece

00:54:46.350 --> 00:54:50.470
of our creativity is used.

00:54:50.470 --> 00:54:55.200
The reason I can support that is

00:54:55.200 --> 00:55:00.630
because as I was saying earlier
we all start off learning

00:55:00.630 --> 00:55:02.270
from other people.

00:55:02.270 --> 00:55:07.060
And for me, balanced in the
context of American culture,

00:55:07.060 --> 00:55:10.720
I hate to bring that
up, I hate to separate,

00:55:10.720 --> 00:55:18.170
I feel that it allows
for creativity.

00:55:18.170 --> 00:55:23.130
Having said that,
I 100% understand.

00:55:23.130 --> 00:55:26.270
I'm 100% for autonomy.

00:55:26.270 --> 00:55:30.890
And in a perfect universe,

00:55:30.890 --> 00:55:34.100
I think that I would
probably go a different way,

00:55:34.100 --> 00:55:35.940
but with the laws
that we have now

00:55:35.940 --> 00:55:38.630
and the way this
country is structured,

00:55:38.630 --> 00:55:40.920
our organization feels

00:55:40.920 --> 00:55:43.500
that compulsory is
what we would support.

00:55:43.500 --> 00:55:52.510
&gt;&gt; David: What was the
section of that act [laughter]?

00:55:52.510 --> 00:55:56.450
I mean I feel pretty much
the same way Melvin does.

00:55:56.450 --> 00:56:02.210
I mean I think people forget
though you can cover a song

00:56:02.210 --> 00:56:05.460
in a venue and it's covered by
a blanket license and in theory

00:56:05.460 --> 00:56:12.360
that whole process was--
until the DOJ stepped in--

00:56:12.360 --> 00:56:16.210
it largely took place
in the private market.

00:56:16.210 --> 00:56:18.960
I see that there
are other countries

00:56:18.960 --> 00:56:20.690
that don't have compulsory
licenses,

00:56:20.690 --> 00:56:24.590
but that have private market
solutions or free market more

00:56:24.590 --> 00:56:29.850
or less solutions to trying
to license compulsories

00:56:29.850 --> 00:56:31.320
for covers and stuff like that.

00:56:31.320 --> 00:56:37.730
The problem with the
compulsory licenses is the

00:56:37.730 --> 00:56:39.280
economic problem.

00:56:39.280 --> 00:56:44.770
I think most people don't mind
having their songs covered.

00:56:44.770 --> 00:56:48.720
So I'm against the
compulsory license

00:56:48.720 --> 00:56:52.600
because it's essentially
a subsidy for --

00:56:52.600 --> 00:56:55.480
, mostly because it
ends up being a subsidy

00:56:55.480 --> 00:57:01.980
for winners the government
has picked in advance,

00:57:01.980 --> 00:57:07.570
technology companies, even large
media companies previously.

00:57:07.570 --> 00:57:12.000
So I would rather not have it.

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:13.130
&gt;&gt; Kimberely: Okay I
think this is going

00:57:13.130 --> 00:57:15.370
to be our last question.

00:57:16.390 --> 00:57:17.830
&gt;&gt; Jane Ginsburg: Thanks, I'd
like to ask you the question

00:57:17.830 --> 00:57:22.410
that I was asked at the end of
my talk before lunch, which is,

00:57:22.410 --> 00:57:27.970
you've spoken eloquently about
what moral rights mean for you

00:57:27.970 --> 00:57:32.000
but how is that in
the public interest?

00:57:38.120 --> 00:57:40.010
&gt;&gt; David: I don't know if --

00:57:40.010 --> 00:57:42.180
, moral rights how is it
in the public interest?

00:57:42.180 --> 00:57:43.670
&gt;&gt; Jane: So the question
that I was asked at the end

00:57:43.670 --> 00:57:46.940
of my talk this is very nice
all the good things to say

00:57:46.940 --> 00:57:50.780
about attribution rights but
what's in it for the public?

00:57:50.780 --> 00:57:53.390
The implication of
the question being

00:57:53.390 --> 00:57:57.140
that there is an opposition
between the interest

00:57:57.140 --> 00:58:00.120
of the author in
being recognized

00:58:00.120 --> 00:58:03.030
and the economic benefits that
might flow from that as well

00:58:03.030 --> 00:58:07.010
as the psychological
benefits, but to the extent

00:58:07.010 --> 00:58:11.100
that attribution rights
might make the dissemination

00:58:11.100 --> 00:58:14.540
of the work more difficult
because you get bogged

00:58:14.540 --> 00:58:17.150
down in trying to find
out who is the author

00:58:17.150 --> 00:58:20.480
and identify the author so
we have less dissemination

00:58:20.480 --> 00:58:23.440
of the work to the public.

00:58:23.440 --> 00:58:28.600
What's the argument from
the author, as an author?

00:58:28.600 --> 00:58:30.560
I gave the law professor
answer [laughter] -

00:58:30.560 --> 00:58:34.000
&gt;&gt; [Name]: Okay,
pretty good answer.

00:58:34.000 --> 00:58:39.400
&gt;&gt; Jane: What as authors can you
say about why recognizing you

00:58:39.400 --> 00:58:42.670
as the creators of your
work, why is that good

00:58:42.670 --> 00:58:45.230
for the public in general?

00:58:45.230 --> 00:58:50.300
&gt;&gt; Can I take a quick
swipe at that one?

00:58:50.300 --> 00:58:58.850
I believe that all of the rules
and laws we have are aimed

00:58:58.850 --> 00:59:02.120
at stimulating creative
activity.

00:59:02.120 --> 00:59:09.610
And if your work can be taken
without attribution, it,

00:59:09.610 --> 00:59:15.510
to some, is going to be a
disincentive to doing it.

00:59:15.510 --> 00:59:21.100
And again you know as
somebody who's privileged

00:59:21.100 --> 00:59:27.720
to have wide readership,
and who doesn't pass a day

00:59:27.720 --> 00:59:34.150
without getting fan mail, you
know I feel blessed by that,

00:59:34.150 --> 00:59:35.960
by the relationship
that I've entered

00:59:35.960 --> 00:59:38.880
into with all of those people.

00:59:38.880 --> 00:59:46.130
And if you told me-- leaving
aside the incredible good

00:59:46.130 --> 00:59:48.990
fortune financially
that I've also enjoyed--

00:59:48.990 --> 00:59:52.810
that that could be
taken away from me

00:59:52.810 --> 00:59:58.590
because attribution would
no longer be required,

00:59:58.590 --> 01:00:01.120
that would be a huge loss.

01:00:01.120 --> 01:00:05.230
It would change the meaning
of authorship and I'm sure

01:00:05.230 --> 01:00:08.180
for many authors
and other creators

01:00:08.180 --> 01:00:10.950
that it's a disincentive.

01:00:10.950 --> 01:00:14.670
If you're saying that
there are certain mishaps

01:00:14.670 --> 01:00:17.910
in the internet world
that we all know

01:00:17.910 --> 01:00:22.030
about where attribution
gets lost that's one thing,

01:00:22.030 --> 01:00:24.440
but if you're saying
that attribution

01:00:24.440 --> 01:00:28.160
in general is no longer
going to be a right

01:00:28.160 --> 01:00:31.490
that we value I truly believe

01:00:31.490 --> 01:00:38.190
that you have diminished
the glory of authorship.

01:00:38.190 --> 01:00:40.480
&gt;&gt; Sean: I'll take a slightly
different crack if I could

01:00:40.480 --> 01:00:42.880
at that which is I agree
with that, but I also think

01:00:42.880 --> 01:00:45.560
that what it gets you is it
gets you that public sphere,

01:00:45.560 --> 01:00:47.480
that public discourse.

01:00:47.480 --> 01:00:49.600
And that's what I was trying
to really hone in on today,

01:00:49.600 --> 01:00:52.040
is that we had at
times in the past,

01:00:52.040 --> 01:00:53.960
as Professor Ginsburg
knows, that with a lot

01:00:53.960 --> 01:00:55.770
of scientific societies
going back

01:00:55.770 --> 01:00:57.180
into the early scientific
revolution,

01:00:57.180 --> 01:00:58.530
and yes copyright was important

01:00:58.530 --> 01:01:01.510
on the science side not just
creative arts, it was a lot

01:01:01.510 --> 01:01:05.310
of manuscript culture of things
being circulated privately

01:01:05.310 --> 01:01:07.840
and partly because people
weren't ready to take that stand

01:01:07.840 --> 01:01:10.130
and they needed some
other incentives to do it.

01:01:10.130 --> 01:01:12.080
So what does moral rights
and attribution gets you?

01:01:12.080 --> 01:01:13.420
Well it's what copyright
gets you as well.

01:01:13.420 --> 01:01:14.970
It gets people putting
their stuff

01:01:14.970 --> 01:01:17.920
out there publicly releasing
it not necessarily free

01:01:17.920 --> 01:01:19.930
economically, but
putting it out there

01:01:19.930 --> 01:01:22.750
so it could be a
robust public discourse.

01:01:22.750 --> 01:01:26.620
&gt;&gt; Melvin: I would tag onto
that I mean going somewhere

01:01:26.620 --> 01:01:28.630
that I wouldn't rarely
go in public,

01:01:28.630 --> 01:01:30.150
going a little Darwinian.

01:01:30.150 --> 01:01:36.280
I think that in attribution you
might actually have a situation

01:01:36.280 --> 01:01:38.020
where the best people win.

01:01:38.020 --> 01:01:40.480
I mean I talked to a
couple of friends of mine

01:01:40.480 --> 01:01:42.190
who were professional
ghostwriters.

01:01:42.190 --> 01:01:47.150
Nobody really wanted to share a
song so I'm just going to have

01:01:47.150 --> 01:01:48.970
to riff one of my own on this

01:01:48.970 --> 01:01:52.830
but ghostwriting is not a
new thing but who knows,

01:01:52.830 --> 01:01:55.070
who knows if the person
who actually was painting

01:01:55.070 --> 01:01:56.890
for Rembrandt maybe
that's the person

01:01:56.890 --> 01:01:58.320
who should have been famous.

01:01:58.320 --> 01:02:01.100
Because we don't have
attribution we'll never

01:02:01.100 --> 01:02:02.600
really know.

01:02:02.600 --> 01:02:04.660
I think, and in the context
of the music business,

01:02:04.660 --> 01:02:08.410
the way the music business
is in 2016, I know that a lot

01:02:08.410 --> 01:02:13.370
of people go uncredited
that are propping up a lot

01:02:13.370 --> 01:02:20.080
of other people's careers and
I think that it would be better

01:02:20.080 --> 01:02:21.790
for the people of
the world if some

01:02:21.790 --> 01:02:23.890
of these talented people
actually got to get out from

01:02:23.890 --> 01:02:26.540
under these other people and got
known for what they were doing.

01:02:26.540 --> 01:02:28.120
It would make the
music world better.

01:02:28.120 --> 01:02:28.610
It just would.

